[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(33) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Paul besought them all to take meat.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Better, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to take food;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and so in the next verse. Once again the practical insight of the Apostle—yet more, perhaps, his kindly human sympathy—comes prominently forward. Soldiers and sailors needed something that would draw them together after the incident just narrated. All were liable at once to the despair and the irritability caused by exhaustion.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That ye have tarried and continued fasting, having taken nothing.—Better, that ye continue on the look-out, without a meal, taking no extra food. The English somewhat exaggerates the force of the Greek. The word for “fasting” is not that which is commonly used in the New Testament to express entire abstinence from food. It was physically impossible that the two hundred and seventy-six who were on board could have gone on for fourteen days without any food at all. Scanty rations had, we must believe, been doled out to those who came for them; but the tension of suspense was so great that they had not sat down to any regular meal. They had taken, as the last word implies, nothing beyond what was absolutely necessary to keep body and soul together. What they wanted physically was food, and morally, the sense of restored companionship; and to this St. Paul’s advice led them.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "That ye have tarried and continued fasting, having taken nothing.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Better, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "that ye continue on the look-out, without a meal, taking no extra food.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " The English somewhat exaggerates the force of the Greek. The word for “fasting” is not that which is commonly used in the New Testament to express entire abstinence from food. It was physically impossible that the two hundred and seventy-six who were on board could have gone on for fourteen days without any food at all. Scanty rations had, we must believe, been doled out to those who came for them; but the tension of suspense was so great that they had not sat down to any regular meal. They had taken, as the last word implies, nothing beyond what was absolutely necessary to keep body and soul together. What they wanted physically was food, and morally, the sense of restored companionship; and to this St. Paul’s advice led them.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Acts 27:33-38",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 27:33-38",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "While the day was coming on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Before they had light sufficient to discern what they should do; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Paul besought them all to take meat — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To take some refreshment; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "saying, This is the fourteenth day that ye continue fasting ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Not as if they had absolutely eaten nothing all that while; for it is generally allowed that none can fast half so long without danger of death; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "having taken nothing ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— No regular meal; through a deep sense of your extreme danger: the necessary consequence of which is, that you must be very faint and weak, and unfit for those exertions and fatigues which may farther lie before you; for it will be a narrow escape that we are to expect, and we may find great difficulties in getting on shore. If a sense of the great danger they were in took away all their desire for food, let us not wonder if men who have a deep sense of the danger they are in of everlasting death should, for a time, forget either to take food, or to attend to their worldly affairs. Much less let us censure that as madness which may be the beginning of true wisdom. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Wherefore ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Since till the morning rises we can attempt nothing by way of approach to land; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I pray ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Παρακαλω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I exhort; you to take ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τροφης",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "nourishment, for this is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Προς της υμετερας σωτηριας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for your preservation, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "that ye may be the better able to swim to shore; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for there shall not a hair, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — A proverbial expression, assuring them of entire safety. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And when he had thus spoken, he took bread and gave thanks ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— For that provision which God now gave them in their necessities, and for the assurance of life with which he had favoured them by so particular a revelation; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and when he had broken it, he began to eat ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Thus setting them an example. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Then were they all of good cheer — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Encouraged by his example as well as words; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and they also took some meat ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— As he had done. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And when they had eaten enough ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— As much as was sufficient for their present refreshment and support; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "they lightened the ship ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Still more than they had done; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and cast out the wheat ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— The very stores they had on board; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "into the sea ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— So firmly did they now depend on what Paul had said. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
